It goes back to Tolkien, I think, where Elves are almost gods, and occasionally a one-in-a-generation extremely studly and impressive human male, like Beren Erchamion, would have the opportunity to hook up with an Elf woman, like Tinuviel.

I do believe Tolkien borrowed this bit from Celtic myth of the leannán sídhe, the woman of Faerie who will take a mortal man as a lover, which dooms him to a short but exciting life.

Tolkien also borrowed from Norse myth, but much less material survives about such topics. Snorri Sturllson speaks of the Ljósálfar, the Light Elves, who are "more beautiful than the sun to look upon," who live in a place called Álfheimr. It's briefly mentioned only twice in the Prose Edda and not at all in any other known primary source and there are no other details.
